The Chronicle Business Reporter
ZIMBABWE is lining up a crucial international indaba on economic growth strategies where experts will deliberate holistically on its impact with the view to transforming them to be innovative. The two-day convention on ‘Zimbabwe’s Economic Growth Strategy: Current Experiences and Way Forward’ is slated for August 10-12 in Victoria Falls, the Ministry of Finance and Economic Development has said. <img class="alignnone wp-image-604060 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-54-6.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-54-6.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-54-6-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" />  According to the ministry, the convention is primed to be an annual event. “The Ministry of Finance and Economic Development in collaboration with other stakeholders is organising an International Convention on Zimbabwe’s Economic Growth Strategy: Current Experiences and Way forward,” the ministry said in a statement. “The objective of the convention is for stakeholders to engage and deliberate holistically on issues that will impact Zimbabwe’s growth strategies to make them more innovative and transformative.  “The convention, which is poised to become an annual event will provide evidence-based policy strategies and policies that should contribute to the achievement of the National Vision 2030,” it added. The convention is set to bring together experts from the world to discuss and analyse Zimbabwe’s growth strategies and to proffer solutions and recommendations in line with broad pillars, which include informal sector development and poverty reduction, industrialisation and trade policy and public and private investments and creation of an enabling environment for business. Monetary and exchange rate policy and fiscal policy reforms will be under the spotlight. <img class="alignnone wp-image-604057 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-53-7.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-53-7.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/04/Untitled-53-7-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> This year, the economy is projected to grow by 5,5 percent, leveraging on the peaceful environment, increased production and productivity, infrastructural development, a buoyant mining sector as well as a recovering tourism and hospitality industry. According to the National Export Strategy for Zimbabwe, one of the key deliverables is to diversify exports. The National Development Strategy 1 (NDS1) also targets to grow exports by 10 per cent every year up to 2023. According to ZimTrade, the country’s national trade promotion body, last year the country managed 13 percent export growth, which is above 10 percent.